The Curtiss R3C was an airplane race american built versions of land and seaplane. It was the only biplane single-seater built by the Curtiss Aeroplane and Motor Company.The R3C-1Also given the "paper" designation F3C as fighters in the US Navy designation system: Swanborough and Bowers 1976, p 127. is the version of earth that Cyrus Bettis rode to win the Pulitzer Trophy Race on 12 October 1925, at a speed of 248,9&#x20;mph (406.5&#x20;km/h).The R3C-2 is the version seaplane twin floats built for the Coupe Schneider. In 1925 the race took place in the Chesapeake Bay in Baltimore, Maryland. Has 232.57&#x20;mph (374.274&#x20;km/h), Jimmy Doolittle won the trophy with a Curtiss R3C-2. The other two R3C-2, piloted by George Cuddihy and Ralph Oftsie, didn't joint the finish line. The next day, with the same plane on a straight line, Doolittle reached 245.7&#x20;mph (395.4&#x20;km/h), a new world record. For the Trophy for the Schneider, which occurred on November 13, 1926, the engine of the R3C-2 was improved and the pilot Christian Frank Schilt won the second place with 231.364&#x20;mph (372.34&#x20;km/h).
Copy survivantLe R3C-2 cup winner Schneider 1925 piloted by Jimmy Doolitle is preserved at the National Air and Space Museum. He is still wearing his race number "3" of 1925.
